    <button class="question">Heart Disease Diagnosis Symptoms</button>
    <div class="answer">
        <h3 style="color: green;">1. Resting Blood Pressure (in mm Hg)</h3>
        <p>This refers to the pressure in your arteries when your heart is resting between beats. A higher resting blood pressure may indicate potential heart disease.</p>

        <h3 style="color: green;">2. Serum Cholesterol</h3>
        <p>Cholesterol is a fatty substance in the blood that can build up in the arteries, leading to blockages. High serum cholesterol levels can increase the risk of heart disease.</p>

        <h3 style="color: green;">3. Fasting Blood Sugar > 120 mg/dl</h3>
        <p>Fasting blood sugar is the blood glucose level after an overnight fast. Elevated levels can indicate diabetes, which is a risk factor for heart disease.</p>

        <h3 style="color: green;">4. Exercise-Induced Angina</h3>
        <p>Angina is chest pain or discomfort caused by reduced blood flow to the heart. Exercise-induced angina occurs during physical exertion and can indicate heart disease.</p>

        <h3 style="color: green;">5. ST Depression Induced by Exercise Relative to Rest (Oldpeak)</h3>
        <p>Oldpeak refers to the difference in the ST segment of an ECG before and after exercise. ST depression during exercise is a sign of reduced oxygen supply to the heart muscle, which may indicate heart disease.</p>

        <h3 style="color: green;">6. The Slope of the Peak Exercise ST Segment (Slope): Upsloping, Flat, Downsloping</h3>
        <p>This measures the shape of the ST segment during exercise on an ECG. A downsloping ST segment is associated with a higher risk of heart disease, while an upsloping segment is considered normal.</p>

        <h3 style="color: green;">7. Number of Major Vessels (0-4) Colored by Fluoroscopy</h3>
        <p>This test measures the number of coronary arteries that are blocked or narrowed, with fluoroscopy used to highlight them. The higher the number of affected vessels, the greater the risk of heart disease.</p>

        <h3 style="color: green;">8. Chest Pain Type</h3>
        <p>Chest pain is categorized into:
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Typical Angina:</strong> Pain caused by restricted blood flow to the heart, often triggered by physical exertion.</li>
                <li><strong>Atypical Angina:</strong> Pain not caused by physical exertion but still related to heart issues.</li>
                <li><strong>Non-Anginal Pain:</strong> Chest pain not related to the heart.</li>
                <li><strong>Asymptomatic:</strong> No pain present despite heart disease.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>

        <h3 style="color: green;">9. Resting Electrocardiographic (ECG) Results</h3>
        <p>The resting ECG measures the electrical activity of the heart. Abnormal results can indicate heart problems. The common types of abnormal results include:
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Normal:</strong> No signs of heart disease.</li>
                <li><strong>ST-T Wave Abnormality:</strong> Indicates possible issues with heart muscle oxygenation.</li>
                <li><strong>Left Ventricular Hypertrophy:</strong> Enlargement of the heart's left ventricle, which may signal heart disease.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>

        <h3 style="color: green;">10. Thalassemia</h3>
        <p>Thalassemia refers to abnormalities in the hemoglobin of red blood cells. It is categorized into:
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Normal:</strong> No abnormalities.</li>
                <li><strong>Fixed Defect:</strong> A permanent abnormality, often linked to heart disease.</li>
                <li><strong>Reversible Defect:</strong> A temporary abnormality, which can sometimes be reversed with treatment.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </div>
